                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;@iwein giving GET request bodies meaning is in fact &lt;i&gt;not&lt;/i&gt; a violation of the spec. &lt;a href=&quot;https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2616#section-4.3&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer&quot;&gt;HTTP/1.1&lt;/a&gt; specifies that servers SHOULD ignore the body, but &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2119.txt&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer&quot;&gt;RFC 2119&lt;/a&gt; specifies that implementers are allowed to ignore &quot;SHOULD&quot; clauses if they have good reason to do so. Rather, a client &lt;i&gt;does&lt;/i&gt; violate the spec if it assumes that changing the GET body will &lt;i&gt;not&lt;/i&gt; change the response.&lt;/span&gt;

